passages.text: Earnings Review: 1H25A at;ove expectation; acquisition drives positive surprise in traditional seeds; maintain Buy
002385.SZ 12m Price Target: Rmb8.00 Price: Rmb4.23 Upside: \(89.1\%\)

DBN reported 1H25A net profit of Rmb235mn, or EPS of Rmb0.055/sh, versus loss of Rmb0.036/sh in 1H24A. Excluding one- off items including investment gain on equity disposal, government subsidy, fair value gain, and other extraordinary items, recurring net profit was Rmb196mn, versus loss of Rmb244mn in 1H24A. The results were above our estimates on higher traditional seed profit, but likely behind Refinitiv consensus. DBN declared no final dividend in 1H25A, same as last year.

We revise recurring earnings estimates for DBN by - 25% in 2025E, to incorporate lower hog pricing assumptions versus prior, - 4% in 2026E, and - 9% in 2027E. The inclusion of Longjing acquisition has led to positive surprises in traditional seeds revenue and margin. While non- seeds operations in feed and hog farming tend to be cyclical and lack structural improvement, we continue to view DBN's dominant position in bio- tech seeds trait will drive a transformation of the company in the coming years. We expect DBN's trait revenue to reach Rmb116mn in 2025E (7% of EBIT), followed by Rmb532mn (or 15% of EBIT) in 2026E, and Rmb1.9bn in a scenario where industry bio- tech seeds penetration reaches 90%, or equivalent to 118% of 2025E EBIT, equivalent to Rmb5.2/sh in valuation. Maintain Buy on DBN with 12- m target price of Rmb8.0/sh (unchanged).

On hog farming production, we lowered gross profit by \(14\%\) in 2025E, to factor in softer pricing in 3Q25A. We maintain our improving hog pricing outlook for domestic market, at Rmb16.5/kg in 2026E, driven by supply discipline, versus Rmb14.8/kg in 1H25A. However, we revised up DBN's hog sales volume (incl. subsidiary) by \(6\%\) in 2025E, and \(15\%\) in 2026E, driven by sow herd addition since 2H24A, and potentially higher PSY, from introduction of high- quality breeding hogs.

On biotech seeds, we expected DBN to continue benefiting from its dominant trait share in the domestic market, to generate Rmb116mn of additional revenue in 2025E ( \(7\%\) of total EBIT), lower versus prior estimate, due to lower than expected industry penetration of \(7\%\) (from \(10\%\) ) during 24/25 planting season, and Rmb532mn in 2026E ( \(15\%\) of EBIT). Policy deregulation and DBN's market shares remain on track, reflected in higher geographic coverage (as \(90\%\) of domestic corn planting), ongoing industry penetration, and affirmation on trait payment and pricing premium (vs. traditional seed). The company's increasing focus on IP protection, and MOA's crackdown on misinformation of biotech seed (link), is also expected to support company's trait earning growth in the coming years.

We also revise up gross profit assumption for company's traditional seed by \(3\%\) in 2026E, and \(4\%\) in 2027E, driven by potential market gain in Southwestern regions, supported by promotion of key products in corn and hybrid seeds, and potential acquisition opportunities in other major corn planting regions.

Feed operation ( \(56\%\) of total gross profit): Gross profit from feed operation was better than expected, driven by higher sales volume and unit gross profit. Unit feed profit was Rmb417/t, \(10\%\) low yoy, consistent with pricing decline trend, partly offset by lower corn and soybean meal purchase price during period. Overall feed sales was \(2\%\) higher yoy, with increasing hog feed penetration in small- and mid- sized hog farms, partly offset by decline in aqua and ruminant feed.

Hog farming operation (29% of total gross profit): Gross profit from hog farming was lower than expectation, mostly due to lower unit hog gross profit. Total unit cost of market hog lowered to Rmb13.1/kg by estimate, down 16%, or Rmb2.5/kg yoy, driven by lower unit feed cost (Rmb1.3/kg), and lower unit SG&A+fin (Rmb0.9/kg), but above our estimate on higher unit D&A. Sales volume of market hog (incl. subsidiary) was 3.8mn head, 35% higher yoy, on the back of improved PSY and sow addition since 2H24A. By end of 1H25A, total sow herd size was 0.28mn head, 10% high versus end of 2024A. Company also reported investment gain from its hog farming subsidiary at Rmb143mn, versus Rmb4mn a year ago.

Traditional seed operation (9% of total gross profit): Gross profit from seed operation was above expectation, driven by higher unit gross profit and sales volume, from hybrids rice and corn seeds. The improvement was mostly driven by expanding promotion area for its key varieties in Southwestern regions, supported by yield performance and expanding sales network. DBN also completed its acquisition on Longjing ("龙粳") Seed in 2H24, with estimated Rmb100mn revenue, mostly from hybrid seed during the period.

Biotech seed operation: Management expected trait license revenue to be 2- 3x higher yoy, driven by higher industry penetration of biotech corn seeds, reaching 7%, or 40mn in 24/25E planting season, versus 2% a year ago. License fee remains competitive, at Rmb8/mu, or 40% of biotech seed pricing premium (vs. traditional seeds), and mostly settled by cash.
Exhibit 3: Numbers of biotech corn seed varieties approved by MOA - 96 varieties using DBN trait, out of 161 in total
Exhibit 4: Biotech seed planting region for crop year 24/25 - covering 90% of domestic corn seed planting area
Source: Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research
Operation costs and others: Total SG&A was above expectation, on higher salary and marketing expense during the period.

Cash flow: Operating cash flow turn positive in 1H25A, versus negative Rmb190mn a year ago, most inline with profit trend. Working capital was mostly inline with past seasonality. FCF was negative Rmb363mn in 1H25A versus negative Rmb593mn a year ago. CAPEX was mostly stable yoy, on feed processing plant, and seed breeding center.
Balance sheet and gearing: Net debt was Rmb8.14bn as of end of 1H25A, with net
gearing at \(93\%\) , versus \(86\%\) at the end of 2024A.

Our valuation is based on average of near- term and long- term valuations. We use DBN's past 12- month average P/E of 15x to arrive at our near- term valuation for 2026E (rolling from 2025E). Our long- term valuation is based on SOTP, including 8x P/E on feed, 8x P/E on hog, 20x on traditional seeds, and 20x on plant and animal protection for 2030E, then discount back at a rate of \(10\%\) to 2026E (rolling from 2025E). We also value DBN's GMO business based on exit P/E of 40x for 2030E. Our target price implies a P/E of 34x for 2025E, and 15x for 2026E.

Key risks: 1) Uncertainty in hog prices that can be affected by industry supply changes, including both domestic supply and imports, and the potential launch of an ASF vaccine that could materially impact both supply and costs; 2) lower- than- expected feed consumption demand for high- end hog products; 3) slower- than- expected government plan of GM seed commercialization.

Dabeinong (DBN) is a diversified agriculture products producer involved in animal feed, hog farming, seed breeding and other businesses. In 2024A, feed constituted \(66\%\) of DBN's total sales, followed by \(22\%\) from hog farming, \(6\%\) from traditional seeds, and \(6\%\) from other business. While non- seeds operations in feed and hog farming tend to be cyclical and lack structural improvement, we continue to view DBN's dominant position in bio- tech seeds trait will drive a transformation of the company in the coming years. We expect DBN's trait revenue to reach Rmb116mn in 2025E (7% of EBIT), followed by Rmb532mn (or \(15\%\) of EBIT) in 2026E, and Rmb1.9bn in a scenario where industry bio- tech seeds penetration reaches \(90\%\) , or equivalent to \(118\%\) of 2025E EBIT, equivalent to Rmb5.2/sh in valuation. We are Buy rated on DBN given its market leading position in the domestic GM market, with current valuation yet to capture its GM- related upside potential.

Risks to our view are 1) uncertainty in hog prices that can be affected by industry supply changes, including both domestic supply and imports, and the potential launch of an ASF vaccine that could materially impact both supply and costs; 2) lower- than- expected feed consumption demand for high- end hog products; 3) slower- than- expected government plan of GM seed commercialization.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
